alex.mojaki.boxes

Enum Boxes

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<Boxes>
      • alex.mojaki.boxes.Boxes
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<Boxes>

    public enum Boxes
extends Enum<Boxes>
    Container for static factory methods producing boxes of various kinds.

    The various box methods are just intended to be more convenient than their corresponding constructors, especially in Java 6 which doesn't have the diamond operator. The disadvantage is that type inference doesn't work anymore if you try chaining, i.e. this will work:

    PowerBox<Integer> x = box(Example.class, "x");

    but this won't:

    PowerBox<Integer> x = box(Example.class, "x").addChangeObserver(ChangePrinter.I);

    so you'll have to resort to:

    PowerBox<Integer> x = new CommonBox<>(Example.class, "x").addChangeObserver(ChangePrinter.I);

      • upgrade

        public static <T> PowerBox<T> upgrade(BoxFamily family,
                                      Box<T> box)
        Return a PowerBox with the given family that forwards get and set to the given box.

        The return value is meant to replace the box argument by direct reassignment, i.e.

        exampleObject.boxField = Boxes.upgrade(family, exampleObject.boxField);

        This essentially makes it possible for a user to add observers and middleware to a plain Box. However they may be bypassed if a reference to the original box has been held elsewhere.
